[1] Kentucky
Date: Thu 3 Jan 2019
Source: WKYT [edited]
https://www.wkyt.com/content/news/Central-Kentucky-counties-continue-to-see-upswing-in-hepatitis-A-cases-503854821.html


Some central Kentucky counties are continuing to see an upswing in hepatitis A cases. One of those counties is Fayette County. The Lexington-Fayette County Health Department says it has seen more than 85 cases in November and December 2018 alone, bringing the total to 124.

"I think it's finally just reached more momentum here in Lexington, especially among high-risk groups," commissioner of health Kraig Humbaugh said. "So 75% to 80% of our cases are folks who use substances, but we have to remind people that 10% to 15% of the cases here in Lexington, we don't know of any risk factors."

The state numbers are showing no signs of slowing down either. There are now more than 3200 cases as of mid-December 2018. More than 20 have died as a result.

Experts are urging the public to get vaccinated and to practice proper handwashing. To have full immunity, you should get 2 shots. The 2nd dose is given at least 6 months after the 1st one. Only 90% of people are protected against the virus after the 1st shot.

[Byline: Lauren Minor]

