[2] Tennessee
Date: Wed 2 Jan 2019
Source: WKRN [edited]
https://www.wkrn.com/news/local-news/hepatitis-a-continues-to-spread-in-nashville/1683874779


There are now 166 people in Nashville, Tennessee, who have contracted hepatitis A. That brings the state total to 636 confirmed cases. That is an increase from the numbers last released on 19 Dec 2018, which were 161 confirmed cases in Nashville and 597 cases statewide. The outbreak began in December 2017; 2 people have died. The increase comes while state and local health departments are working to contain and end Tennessee's hepatitis A outbreak.

"If you look at those who are at risk that includes people who use drugs and [are] homeless. Those 2 populations can end up in the jail system," said Metro Nashville Health Department spokesman Brian Todd. "[We] focus on them and work with the Sheriff's office to offer the [vaccination] to all inmates when they enter the system." The health department cannot force people to get the vaccine.

In Nashville, health officials usually see one or 2 cases of hepatitis A per year. Right now, they are seeing 2 cases per week. That number is down from the peak during summer 2018, when the health department reported about 10 confirmed cases of the virus each week. Todd says the number may peak again because it can take up to 12 months to end a hepatitis A outbreak.

"We're going to continue to focus on those at-risk groups and being able to reach those at-risk groups with the vaccine," said Todd. "We're also putting out messages about how to stop the spread, that includes handwashing to remove the germs that may cause someone to be sick."

Drug users and men who have sex with men are also at risk. The Nashville Health Department has been out to various LGBTQ nightclubs where nurses will set up inside and offer vaccinations.

Hepatitis A spreads from human waste. That's why it's crucial to wash your hands after you go to the bathroom.

It is now a requirement that children be vaccinated for hepatitis A before they go to school. That is a semi-recent development. Current 21-year-olds are among the 1st group who were vaccinated as infants.

[Byline: Jessica Jaglois]

