[As the numbers of cases continue to rise in a number of states and news of smaller (so far) outbreaks occur in others, the question asked at the end of the last post is more and more relevant. We are seeing these outbreaks because of the inability and, in part, lack of desire of local governments to deal with marginalized populations among their midst. The dramatic cutbacks in the public health infrastructure in some of these states clearly feeds the fire of these outbreaks. To blame the entire outbreak on restaurants (that reflect the overflow into food workers but has yet made much of an impact on the restaurants' patrons) is fool-hearty. It must be addressed by bolstering public health resources and education and directly addressing the needs of these marginalized populations. The restaurant risk is an easier fix, just require all food handlers to be immunized against hepatitis A virus.

No new numbers from the leading states, Kentucky and West Virginia, have been published in at least 2 weeks. - Mod.LL

